description:
&lt;p&gt;The South West Regional Operations Centre (ROC) is now being established to manage the expected support required to coordinate the delivery of services to our patients and to support local healthcare professionals and Systems in delivering required services, during what may be a challenging period. The ROC will be responsible for communicating COVID-19, Winter and EU Exit Transition requirements to Providers, Commissioners and other organisations that support healthcare delivery in the South West Region; assuring local preparations; responding to operational enquiries for COVID-19, Winter and EU Exit Transition; coordinating the operational response within the South West Region and meeting national reporting requirements for COVID-19, Winter and EU Exit Transition.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We are looking for energetic and committed team members to bring their skill set and experience to the role and support in the delivery of this vital function. Learning, continuous improvement, growth and development will be fully supported and encouraged.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As the ROC Administration Support, the post holder will work as part of a dynamic team in delivering an effective service supporting local organisations across the Region to maintain a high level of preparedness and delivery for CoVid-19, Winter and EU Exit Transition. The post holder will be responsible for ensuring the delivery of administration services and processes including;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Monitor, review and seek updates to maintain action trackers, risk registers and issues logs.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Meeting management; arranging meetings, minute taking, distributing documentation as required, ensuring invite lists are managed and up to date.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Chase missing reports/SitReps/information as required.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Support other administration activities across ROC as required.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The ROC Administration Support will generally work a 12-hour shift pattern (0800 – 2000) and support the ROC function 7 days a week (37.5 hour working week), including Saturday and Sunday working. Shifts may be split. The weekend working requirements will be undertaken on a rota basis, unless volunteers are found to regularly work at the weekend. Additionally, there may be a requirement for the successful candidate to provide cross-cover for other members of the ROC, including flexing working hours in line with ROC core operating hours and undertaking other tasks and activities as specified by the ROC Manager.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;While the primary location for the South West ROC is in South West House, Taunton, following a period of induction, the successful candidate will generally work remotely, using MS Teams, following current NHS workforce guidance.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When the ROC is able to return to an office base environment, the successful candidate’s location may include SW House, Jenner House, Chippenham or Peninsula House in Saltash.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The reason for the fixed term contract is because this a short-term time limited project.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Interviews will take place virtually via MS Teams.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For further details / informal visits contact:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Nina Barnard, Workforce Manager; n.barnard1@nhs.net&lt;/p&gt;
